[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] In some ways, the history of programming language theory predates even the development of programming languages.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] The lambda calculus, developed by Alonzo Church and Stephen Cole Kleene in the 1930s, is considered by some to be the world's first programming language, even though it was intended to *model* computation rather than being a means for programmers to *describe* algorithms to a computer system.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Many modern functional programming languages have been described as providing a "thin veneer" over the lambda calculus, and many are described easily in terms of it.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] The first programming language to be invented was Plankalkül, which was designed by Konrad Zuse in the 1940s, but not publicly known until 1972, and not implemented until 1998.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] The first widely known and successful high-level programming language was FORTRAN (for Formula Translation), developed from 1954 to 1957 by a team of IBM researchers led by John Backus.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] The success of FORTRAN led to the formation of a committee of scientists to develop a "universal" computer language; the result of their effort was ALGOL 58.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Separately, John McCarthy of Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) developed Lisp, the first language with origins in academia to be successful.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] With the success of these initial efforts, programming languages became an active topic of research in the 1960s and beyond.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] There are several fields of study that either lie within programming language theory, or which have a profound influence on it; many of these have considerable overlap.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] In addition, PLT makes use of many other branches of mathematics, including computability theory, category theory, and set theory.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Formal semantics is the formal specification of the behaviour of computer programs and programming languages.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Three common approaches to describe the semantics or "meaning" of a computer program are denotational semantics, operational semantics and axiomatic semantics.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Type theory is the study of type systems; which are "a tractable syntactic method for proving the absence of certain program behaviors by classifying phrases according to the kinds of values they compute".
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Many programming languages are distinguished by the characteristics of their type systems.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Program analysis is the general problem of examining a program and determining key characteristics (such as the absence of classes of program errors).
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Program transformation is the process of transforming a program in one form (language) to another form.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Comparative programming language analysis seeks to classify languages into different types based on their characteristics; broad categories of languages are often known as programming paradigms.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Metaprogramming is the generation of higher-order programs which, when executed, produce programs (possibly in a different language, or in a subset of the original language) as a result.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Domain-specific languages are those constructed to efficiently solve problems in a given domain, or part of such.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Compiler theory is the theory of writing *compilers* (or more generally, *translators*); programs that translate a program written in one language into another form.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Run-time systems refer to the development of programming language runtime environments and their components, including virtual machines, garbage collection, and foreign function interfaces.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Conferences are the primary venue for presenting research in programming languages.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/programming-language-theory] Notable journals that publish PLT research include the *ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems* (TOPLAS), *Journal of Functional Programming* (JFP), *Journal of Functional and Logic Programming*, and *Higher-Order and Symbolic Computation*.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-annotation] In computer science, a **type signature** or **type annotation** defines the inputs and outputs of a function, subroutine or method.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-annotation] A type signature includes the number, types, and order of the function's arguments.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-annotation] One important use of a type signature is for function overload resolution, where one particular definition of a function to be called is selected among many overloaded forms.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-annotation] In C and C++, the type signature is declared by what is commonly known as a function prototype.
