[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:type-inference-algorithms/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
